<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
SOE/Verant have taken the wrong approach to this kind of situation (proceduraly).<P>I am a Networking consultant. I travel between my clients designing/fixing/upgradeing/migrating ect their networks. if a user is doing something that the company doesnt want to happen on their computers, their first responce is not "warn/fire them", it is to ask me "can we prevent them from doing ActionX?", and i usually end up installing some sort of product that locks down what they can change, mess with, ect. if the user attempts to break the security i install, they they look at termination ect, because that is malicious, but only then.<P>Why doesnt verant fix the exploits, make the dragon's summoning spell/ability work in 3d, fix land vs water fighting, create better pathing, ect. basicly "make it so they cant do ActionX" instead of going right to ban/suspending them.<P>If they hacked verant to change things so these worked that would be one thing... even worthy of legal action, but when working only with the software/servers that VERANT/SOE created, there is no reason they(SOE/VERANT) cant fix these things. I simply can not believe "the engine doesnt support X", the engine will support what ever you program it to. it may be that it takes a lot of man hours so it not worth your while. that i can accept, as i deal with that frequently. <P>I realize that nothing is bug free, but how long has VERANT/SOE known about these things? many of them have been around since eq launched(pathing, and land/water). The dragon summoning thing has been in the game for more than a year.<P>Another thing, they are obvoisly trying to make an example of this guild. and if they were why dont they say "they did this, and this, and this" in Exacting terms so that others can know how/what was done so they know not to do it. other people might figure out the same things and call it something else, or not know why things work, ect. they did list some things, but it is very vague. i see their reasoning behind this, but i must disagree.<P>So i ask you VERANT/SOE to re-evaluate your policy as to how to deal with this kind of situation. Why not add couple of people to deal with things like this from a programming perspective? it would certainly improve your public relations, as banning people, suspending people, and disbanding guilds looks bad for you no matter what the reason is or how right you are.<P>Now i dont claim to know what happened here, who is right/wrong, who should be banned, ect. I am merely talking about what i percieve to be a flaw in your procedure.<P><BR>Cinedara<BR>43rd level of mental acceleration
