<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Let me preface this reply by stating that I think a lot of these uber-guilds are composed of elitest jerks who think they're god's gift to gaming.  Many of them have no problem with resorting to underhanded tactics or even known exploits to get their way.<P>That being said, I have to side with Conquest on this issue.  It is VERANT'S job to let us know if a particular tactic or place or whathaveyou is considered 'illegal.'  We have absolutely no way to determine this for ourselves.  Players can and will determine the path of least resistance when dealing with given situations.  That is NOT cheating... that is just smart gameplay.  As an example, one of my characters is a Druid while my friend plays a Rogue.  One of the tactics we've employed with great success is for me to pull a mob by snaring it, DoTing it and then zapping it frequently with relatively weak and mana-cheap nukes.  This has the effect of REALLY cheesing of the monster such that it advances on me (while I continue to back out of its melee range) while my friend beats the mob in the back (not to mention getting a continual stream of back-stabs).  Is this cheating?  Afterall, we take almost no damage when employing this tactic.  From our perspective, this is just smart and efficient hunting and managing of a creature's agro.  Verant indicated that Conquest was using various techniques to mitigate the damage their took while fighting this dragon--seems perfectly reasonable to me.  If any of the tactics Conquest was using are considered "exploits" how they hell would they know that?  I have never received any email from Verant or read any patch message which indicated that any of what they were doing was illegal.  Verant invents a crime, finds them guilty and punishes them without any sort of process or procedure.  Now, granted I've never worked in the gaming industry, but this seems like bad business and dreadful customer service to me.
</FONT>
